# requirements.txt — this workspace's pinned stack. Copy to
# requirements.txt (drop the .example suffix) once every pin below is a
# real, released tag — a workspace never runs against a moving target.
#
# Modelled on Jaeger-AI's requirements.txt: the framework + every module
# this workspace depends on are git dependencies (none of them have PyPI
# releases yet), pinned to an exact tag. PEP 508 direct references, not
# `-e ../X` — setuptools' dynamic-dependencies file parser only accepts
# requirement specifiers, not pip's `-e`/`-r` directives.
#
# --- framework (required — every workspace pins this) ---
# TODO: replace @0.9.0 with whatever JaegerOS release this workspace is
# actually proven against (CONVENTIONS.md "Versioning & pinning" — a
# range bump needs the same review a code change would).
jaeger-os @ git+https://github.com/JenkinsRobotics/JaegerOS@0.9.0

# --- the Mind (optional — omit entirely for a headless/body-only
# workspace with no agent attached; e.g. a pure hardware bringup used by
# someone else's Mind over the capability layer) ---
# jaeger-ai @ git+https://github.com/JenkinsRobotics/Jaeger-AI@0.9.0

# --- engine modules this workspace's manifest.toml actually enables ---
# One line per module bound to a slot= in manifest.toml.example. Add or
# remove lines to match — a module listed here with no [[node]] slot=
# binding in the manifest is dead weight; a [[node]] with no matching
# pin here will fail to import at boot.
# jaeger-kokoro-tts @ git+https://github.com/JenkinsRobotics/JaegerKokoroTTS@0.9.0
# jaeger-whisper-stt @ git+https://github.com/JenkinsRobotics/JaegerWhisperSTT@0.9.0

# --- this workspace's own hardware-adapter dependencies (whatever
# topology.yaml's controllers actually need to open their links) ---
pyserial>=3.5
pyzmq>=25.0

# --- PINNING POLICY ---
# Dev clone (this repo, day to day): @master or a broad range is fine —
# you want the latest patch while iterating.
# A DEPLOYED STATION (a real robot, a machine an operator relies on):
# EXACT-PIN every line above to a released tag, never @master and never
# a bare `>=`. A station that silently picks up an upstream change on
# its next `pip install` is not reproducible — see CONVENTIONS.md
# "Versioning & pinning". Re-pin deliberately, one version bump at a
# time, with the same review a code change would get.

# --- dev tooling (uncomment if doing workspace development) ---
# pytest>=8.0
# ruff>=0.4
